{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use British English|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox engineer |honorific_suffix = <!-- {{post-nominals|country=GBR|?|size=100%}} --> |image = Thomas Gainsborough - The Rev. Humphry Gainsborough - Google Art Project.jpg |alt = A head and shoulders painted portrait of Humphrey Gainsborough. |caption = ''The Rev. Humphrey Gainsborough'' by [[Thomas Gainsborough]] (his brother), painted 1770–4 |name = Humphrey Gainsborough |nationality = [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] |birth_date = 1718 |birth_place = England |death_date = {{Death date|1776|8|23|df=y}} |death_place = England |education = |spouse = |parents = |children = |discipline = {{unbulleted list|[[Civil engineer]]|[[Mechanical engineer]]|[[Structural engineer]]}} |institutions = |practice_name = |significant_buildings= |significant_projects = {{unbulleted list|[[Conway's Bridge]]|[[Marsh Lock]]}} |significant_design = {{unbulleted list|[[Door chain]]|[[Drill plough]]|[[Steam engine]]|[[Tide mill]]}} |awards = |signature = }}
Reverend '''Humphrey Gainsborough''' (1718 – 23 August 1776) was an English [[non-conformist]] [[Religious minister|minister]], [[engineer]], and [[inventor]].<ref name="Tyler, 2006">{{cite journal |last=Tyler |first=David |title=Humphrey Gainsborough, 1718–1776: Cleric, Engineer and Inventor |journal=[[Transactions of the Newcomen Society]] |issue=76 |pages=51–81 |year=2006}} Read to the [[Newcomen Society]] at the [[Science Museum (London)|Science Museum]], [[London]], 12 October 2005.</ref>
Humphrey Gainsborough was [[pastor]] to the Independent Church in [[Henley-on-Thames]], [[England]]. He was the brother of the artist [[Thomas Gainsborough]]. He invented the [[drill plough]] (1766), winning a prize of £60 from the [[Royal Society]] for his efforts. He also invented the [[tide mill]] (1761), which allowed a [[mill wheel]] to rotate in either direction, winning a £50 prize from the [[Royal Society of Arts|Society for the Encouragement of Arts]] in [[London]]. In addition, he designed a self-ventilating fish wagon (1762).
[[File:Conway Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 722320.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Conway's Bridge]], designed by Humphrey Gainsborough and built in 1763 at [[Park Place (Berkshire)|Park Place]], named after [[Henry Seymour Conway]] (1721–1795)]] Gainsborough designed [[Conway's Bridge]], built in 1763 at [[Park Place (Berkshire)|Park Place]] close to Henley, an interesting rustic arched stone structure that still carries traffic on the road between [[Wargrave]] and Henley today. In 1768, he improved the slope on the road up the steep White Hill to the east of Henley, straightening it in the process.
In the 1760s, Gainsborough showed a model of a condensing [[steam engine]] to [[James Watt]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Watt had been working independently on improvements to the [[Newcomen steam engine|Newcomen "atmospheric engine"]] and subsequently [[patent]]ed these in 1769. He perhaps included some of – and at least built on – Gainsborough's ideas. Gainsborough is thus probably less well-known than he might have been.
The [[canal lock|lock]], [[weir]] and [[footbridge]] at [[Marsh Lock]], just upstream from Henley on the [[River Thames]], were designed by Gainsborough, together with other early locks from [[Sonning]] to [[Maidenhead]] (1772–73).
A [[blue plaque]] in Gainsborough's honour<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/gainsborough.html | title=Humphrey Gainsborough (1718–1776) | publisher=[[Oxfordshire Blue Plaques Scheme]] | location=UK }}</ref> can be found in the town of [[Henley-on-Thames|Henley]] itself on the gates of the Manse, the house where he lived next to the Christ Church [[United Reformed Church]]. Inside he designed an early [[security chain]] and plate on one of the outside doors, allowing the door to be partially opened, that is still there now. Similar designs are used on many people's front doors today.
==Epitaph== [[Philip Thicknesse]] wrote in ''[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]'' in 1785: {{quote|''… one of the most ingenious men that ever lived, and one of the best that ever died … Perhaps of all the mechanical geniuses this or any nation has produced. Mr&nbsp;Gainsborough was the first.''<ref>{{cite book| last=Thicknesse | first=Philip | work=[[The Gentleman's Magazine]], and Historical Chronicle | title=Character of Mr. Gainsborough | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VaNJAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA931&lpg=PA931 | volume=Volume 55, Part 2 | pages=931–932 | publisher=[[Google Books]] | date=1785 }}</ref>}}
